{{merge to|C string|discuss=Talk:C string#Single page for C string functions|date=October 2011}}
{{lowercase|title=strlen}}
In the [[C standard library]], '''<tt>strlen</tt>''' is a [[String functions (programming)| string function]] that determines the length of a [[C string|C character string]].

==Example usage==
<source lang=c>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main()
{
    char *string = "Hello World";
    printf("%lu\n", (unsigned long)strlen(string));
    return 0;
}
</source>
This program will print the value 11, which is the length of the string "Hello World".
Character strings are stored in an array of a data type called <tt>char</tt>.  The end of a string is found by searching for the first [[null character]] in the array.  

Note importantly that this length does *NOT* include the array entry for the trailing null byte required for the ending character of C strings.  Thus, if you need to copy the C string, you need to allocate a space of strlen() + 1.

==Implementation==
[[FreeBSD]] 6.2 implements <tt>strlen</tt> like so:<ref name="bsd62strlen">{{cite web
 | url = http://www.freebsd.org/cgi/cvsweb.cgi/src/lib/libc/string/strlen.c?rev=1.4
 | title = strlen.c Revision 1.4
 | publisher = FreeBSD
 | date = 2002-03-21 | accessdate = 2009-03-04
}}</ref>

<source lang=c>
size_t strlen(const char * str)
{
    const char *s;
    for (s = str; *s; ++s) {}
    return(s - str);
}
</source>

It is possible to write faster versions in C that examines full machine word rather than byte-by-byte.  [[Hacker's Delight]] has given an algorithm that makes use of [[bitwise operations]] to detect if any of these bytes is nul ('\0').  The current FreeBSD implementation does this.<ref name="bsd9xstrlen">{{cite web
 | url = http://www.freebsd.org/cgi/cvsweb.cgi/src/lib/libc/string/strlen.c?rev=1.10
 | title = strlen.c Revision 1.10
 | publisher = FreeBSD
 | date = 2010-03-13
}}</ref>

Modern C compilers usually provide fast inline versions of <tt>strlen</tt> written in [[assembly language|assembly]], either using the bitwise operation technique or a special instruction provided by certain [[Complex_instruction_set_computer|CISC]] processors. In addition, <tt>strlen</tt> of a quoted string constant is often optimized into a constant integer.

