===Vowels===
{| class="wikitable" !'''Pinyin'''||'''[[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]''' |- | a || [a] |- | e || [ə] |- | ''ê'' || [ɛ] |- | i || [i] |- | ''-i'' (after zh,ch,sh,r) || [ʅ] |- | ''-i'' (after z,c,s) || [ɿ] |- | o || [o] |- | u || [u] |- | ü || [y] |}
* "u" after "j, q, x, y" is pronounced as "ü" (the two dots is omitted in spelling) * "e" after "i, u, ü, y" is pronounced as "ê" (the hat "^" is omitted in spelling) * "e" before "i" is pronounced as "ê" (the hat "^" is omitted in spelling) * "o" before "ng" is pronounced as "u" ("u" is written as "o" in spelling)
===Consonants===
{| cellpadding="5" style="border: 2px solid #ccc;" |b |p |m |f |w |- |d |t |n | |l |- |g |k |ng |h |- |j |q | |x |y |- |zh |ch | |sh |r |- |z |c | |s |- |}
===Basic combinations of vowels and consonants===
{| cellpadding="5" style="border: 2px solid #ccc;" |ai || ei || ao || ou |- |an || en || ang || eng || ong |}
* "ei" is pronounced as "êi" ("êi" is written as "ei" in spelling) * "ong" is pronounced as "ung" ("ung" is written as "ong" in spelling)
===Pronunciation of vowels===
{| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 95%" !'''Pinyin'''||'''[[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]'''||'''Explanation'''||'''Examples''' |- ||''a''|| {{IPA|[a]}}|| as the vowel in "star" without the "r" sound|| b'''à'''b'''a''' (papa) |- ||''e''|| {{IPA|[ə]}}|| as the vowel in "stir"||g'''ē'''g'''e''' (elder brother) |- ||''ê''|| {{IPA|[ɛ]}}|| as the vowel in "th'''ei'''r"||xi'''è'''xi'''e''' (thank) |- ||''i''|| {{IPA|[i]}}|| as the vowel in "bit"||d'''ì'''d'''i''' (younger brother) |- ||''-i (after zh,ch,sh,r)''|| {{IPA|[ʅ]}}|| similar to the consonant "r" in "'''r'''ank", but with the lips spread and with the tongue curled upwards||zh'''ī'''ch'''í''' (support) |- ||''-i (after z,c,s)''|| {{IPA|[ɿ]}}|| similar to the consonant in "'''z'''oo"||z'''ì'''s'''ī''' (selfish) |- ||''o''|| {{IPA|[o]}}|| as the vowel in "law"||lǎop'''o''' (wife) |- ||''u''|| {{IPA|[u]}}|| as the vowel in "food"||m'''ǔ'''qin (mother) |- ||''ü''|| {{IPA|[y]}}|| as in German "üben" or French "lune" (To get this sound, say "ee" with rounded lips)||y'''ǔ'''yán* (language) |}
*The two dots of ü is omitted after "j, q, x, y".
===Pronunciation of consonants===
{| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 95%" !'''Pinyin'''||'''[[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]'''||'''Explanation'''||'''Examples''' |- ||''b''|| {{IPA|[b]}}|| '''b''', as in '''b'''it||'''B'''ěijīng (capital of China) |- ||''p''|| {{IPA|[p]}}|| as in English||'''p'''iányi (cheap), '''p'''iàoliang (beautiful) |- ||''m''|| {{IPA|[m]}}|| as in English||'''m'''iàntiáo (noodles) |- ||''f''|| {{IPA|[f]}}|| as in English||'''f'''ācái (get rich) |- ||''d''|| {{IPA|[d]}}|| '''d''', as in '''d'''ark||'''d'''à (big) |- ||''t''|| {{IPA|[t]}}|| as in English||'''t'''àipíng (peace) |- ||''n''|| {{IPA|[n]}}|| as in English||'''n'''ánrén (man) |- ||''l''|| {{IPA|[l]}}|| as in English||'''l'''ǎorén (old man) |- ||''g''|| {{IPA|[g]}}|| '''g''', as in '''g'''ill, never as <s>lar'''g'''e</s>||'''g'''uójiā (country) |- ||''k''|| {{IPA|[k]}}|| as in English ||'''k'''èrén (guest) |- ||''h''|| {{IPA|[x]}}|| like the English '''h''' if followed by "a"; otherwise it is pronounced more roughly (not unlike the [[w:Scots language|Scots]] '''ch''')||'''h'''ēshuǐ (drink water) |- ||''j''|| {{IPA|[tɕ]}}|| like ''q'', but unaspirated. (To get this sound, first take the sound halfway between '''j'''oke and '''ch'''eck, and then slowly pass it backwards along the tongue until it is entirely clear of the tongue tip.) While this exact sound is not used in English, the closest match is the '''j''' in a'''j'''ar, not the '''s''' in A'''s'''ia; this means that "Beijing" is pronounced like "bay-jing", '''not''' like "beige-ing". You may simply pronounce it as ''zh'' and a Chinese may understand it.||'''j'''iàotáng (church), '''j'''iā (home or family) |- ||''q''|| {{IPA|[tɕʰ]}}|| like '''ch'''urch, but with less of the "ch"/"h" sound; pass it backwards along the tongue until it is free of the tongue tip||shēng'''q'''ì (get angry) |- ||''x''|| {{IPA|[ɕ]}}|| like '''sh''', but with less of the "s" sound. Take the sound and pass it backwards along the tongue until it is clear of the tongue tip; very similar to the final sound in German i'''ch''', Portuguese en'''x'''ada, lu'''x'''o, '''x'''ícara, pu'''x'''a, and to '''h'''uge or '''H'''ugh in some English dialects||'''x'''iǎohái (child), '''X'''izang (Tibet) |- ||''zh''|| {{IPA|[tʂ]}}|| '''ch''' with no aspiration (take the sound halfway between '''j'''oke and '''ch'''urch and curl it upwards); very similar to mer'''g'''er in American English, but not voiced ||'''Zh'''ōngguó (China), '''zh'''áohuǒ (be on fire) |- ||''ch''|| {{IPA|[tʂʰ]}}|| as in '''ch'''in, but with the tongue curled upwards; very similar to nur'''tu'''re in American English, but strongly aspirated||'''ch'''īfàn (have a meal), '''ch'''ǎojià (quarrel) |- ||''sh''|| {{IPA|[ʂ]}}|| as in '''sh'''inbone, but with the tongue curled upwards; very similar to under'''sh'''irt in American English||'''sh'''āmò (desert), '''Sh'''ànghǎi (a big city in China) |- ||''r''|| {{IPA|[ɻ]}}|| similar to the English '''r''' in '''r'''ank, but with the lips spread and with the tongue curled upwards||'''r'''è (hot), '''r'''èqíng (passion) |- ||''z''|| {{IPA|[ts]}}|| unaspirated '''c''' (halfway between be'''ds''' and be'''ts'''), (more common example is su'''ds''')||'''z'''ǎoshànghǎo (good morning!), qī'''z'''i (wife), Zhāng '''Z'''ǐyí (name of a Chinese actress) |- ||''c''|| {{IPA|[tsʰ]}}|| like '''ts''', aspirated (more common example is ca'''ts''')||'''c'''ǎo (grass), '''c'''ì, time |- ||''s''|| {{IPA|[s]}}|| as in '''s'''un||Lha'''s'''a (capital of Xizang (Tibet) Autonomous Region), '''S'''uzhou (capital of the province of Jian'''s'''u, near Shanghai) |- ||''y''|| {{IPA|[j]}}|| as in English||'''y'''uèliang (moon) |- ||''w''|| {{IPA|[w]}}|| as in English||'''w'''àiguórén (foreigner) |- ||''ng''|| {{IPA|[ŋ]}}|| as in English||'''ng''' (What?, Huh?) |}
