The SI unit for energy is Joules (J). One joule is equal to 1kg*m^2*s^-2. A kilo-joule (kJ) is equal to 1000 joules of energy. Calorie (Cal) is used to denote energy stored inside the food or energy used by the body. 1 Cal is equal to 4.184 Joules. Similarly, a kilo-calorie (KCal) is equal to 1000 calories.
Atkinds, Peter. Physical Chemistry. 9th. Oxford University Press, 2009. Print.
{{BookCat}}

SI unit of Force is Newtons (N). 1 Newton is equal to 1 kg*m*s^-2. The basic formula for force is F=ma where F stands for force, m stands for mass in kilograms and a stands for acceleration in m*s^-2. This is the Newton's second law of motion.
Atkinds, Peter. Physical Chemistry. 9th. Oxford University Press, 2009. Print.
{{BookCat}}

The SI unit for Temperature is Kelvin (K). However, Celsius is also often used as a measure of temperature. The formula to convert Celsius to Kelvin is K = C + 273.15. So 25 degrees Celsius will equal to 298.15 Kelvin. 25 degrees Celcius or 298.15 Kelvin is called normal temperature.
Atkinds, Peter. Physical Chemistry. 9th. Oxford University Press, 2009. Print.
{{BookCat}}

The SI unit for Entropy (S) is Joules per Kelvin (J/K). A more positive value of entropy means a reaction is more likely to happen spontaneously.
Atkins, Peter. Physical Chemistry. 9th. Oxford University Press, 2009. Print.
{{BookCat}}

The SI unit for power is Watts(W). One Watt is equal to Joule per second (J/s) or kg*m^2s^-3. Power is equal to Work divided by seconds.
Young, Hugh. University Physics: With modern Physics. 12. Pearson College, 2007. Print.
{{BookCat}}

The SI unit for acceleration is m*s^-2. Acceleration is equal to change in velocity over change in time. Taking a second derivative of speed or first derivative of velocity is equal to acceleration.
Young, Hugh. University Physics: With modern Physics. 12. Pearson College, 2007. Print.
{{BookCat}}

